If we divide a whole into 3 equal parts and shade 2, we have $\frac{2}{3}$.
If we divide the same whole into 6 equal parts and shade 4, we have 
$\frac{4}{6}$.

Both cover the same amount of the whole:
center
tikzpicture
 ll[AtlasSage!60] (0,1) rectangle (2,1.5);
 (0,1) rectangle (3,1.5);
 in {1,2} {
 (,1) – (,1.5);
 }
 at (-0.2,1.25) {$\frac{2}{3}$};

 ll[AtlasSage!60] (0,0) rectangle (2,0.5);
 (0,0) rectangle (3,0.5);
 in {0.5,1,1.5,2,2.5} {
 (,0) – (,0.5);
 }
 at (-0.2,0.25) {$\frac{4}{6}$};
tikzpicture
center
Therefore, $\frac{2}{3} = \frac{4}{6}$.
